GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 970
Short Title: Preventing Algorithmic Rent Fixing. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Longest, Lopez, Morey, and Prather (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 14, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO PREVENT ALGORITHMIC RENT FIXING IN THE RENTAL HOUSING
3 MARKET.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. Chapter 42 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new Article
6 to read:
7 "Article 8.
8 "Prevention of Algorithmic Rent Fixing.
9 "§ 42-80. Definitions.
10 The following definitions apply in this Article:
11 (1) Coordinate or coordinating function. – Any of the following with respect to a
12 service provider:
13 a. Collecting of historical or contemporaneous prices, price changes,
14 supply levels, occupancy rates, or lease or rental contract termination
15 and renewal dates of residential dwelling units from two or more real
16 estate lessors or from public databases.
17 b. Analyzing or processing of the information described in
18 sub-subdivision a. of this subdivision using a system, software, or
19 process that uses computation.
20 c. Recommending rental prices, lease terms, or occupancy levels to a real
21 estate lessor.
22 d. Using a pricing algorithm that uses, incorporates, or was trained with
23 nonpublic competitor data to set the amount of rent for a residential
24 dwelling unit or any other commercial term contained within a
25 residential rental agreement.
26 (2) Nonpublic competitor data. – Nonpublic data that is derived from or otherwise
27 provided by another person that competes in the same market as a person, or
28 a related market. This term does not include information distributed, reported,
29 or otherwise communicated in a way that does not reveal any underlying data
30 from a competitor, such as narrative industry reports, news reports, business
31 commentaries, or generalized industry survey results.
32 (3) Nonpublic data. – Information that is not widely available or easily accessible
33 to the public, including information about price, commercial terms, and
34 related products or services, regardless of whether the data is attributable to a
35 specific competitor or anonymized.
*H970-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Person. – As defined in G.S. 12-3.
2 (5) Pre-dispute arbitration agreement. – An agreement to arbitrate a dispute that
3 has not yet arisen at the time of the making of the agreement.
4 (6) Pre-dispute joint-action waiver. – An agreement, whether or not part of a
5 pre-dispute arbitration agreement that would prohibit, or waive the right of,
6 one of the parties to the agreement to participate in a joint, class, or collective
7 action in a judicial, arbitral, administrative, or other forum, concerning a
8 dispute that has not yet arisen at the time of the making of the agreement.
9 (7) Pricing algorithm. – Any process using calculations that analyzes data for the
10 purpose of recommending or setting prices or commercial terms, including
11 processes that utilize machine learning or other artificial intelligence
12 techniques.
13 (8) Real estate lessor. – Any individual, corporation, partnership, association,
14 joint-stock company, trust, or unincorporated organization that owns and
15 leases real property or any portion thereof in the form of a residential dwelling
16 unit.
17 (9) Residential dwelling unit. – Any house, apartment, accessory unit, or other
18 housing unit intended to be used as a person's primary residence. This term
19 does not include inpatient medical care, licensed long-term care, or detention
20 or correctional facilities.
21 (10) Service provider. – A person that provides a coordinating function for a real
22 estate lessor.
23 "§ 42-81. Unlawful coordination.
24 (a) It is unlawful for any real estate lessor, or any agent or subcontractor of a real estate
25 lessor, within North Carolina to subscribe to, contract for, or otherwise exchange anything of
26 value in return for coordinating functions.
27 (b) It is unlawful for any service provider to facilitate an agreement to not compete among
28 real estate lessors with respect to residential dwelling units within the State of North Carolina.
29 "§ 42-82. Enforcement.
30 (a) A violation of any provision of this Article constitutes an unfair or deceptive trade
31 practice under G.S. 75-1.1. Any party aggrieved by a violation of this Article may bring a cause
32 of action against the real estate lessor or service provider, as appropriate, and is entitled to the
33 relief available in Chapter 75 of the General Statutes. The Attorney General is hereby empowered
34 to enforce this Article as allowed by Chapter 75 of the General Statutes.
35 (b) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, at the election of the person alleging
36 conduct constituting a violation of this section, or the named representative of a class in a
37 collective action alleging such conduct, no pre-dispute arbitration agreement or pre-dispute
38 joint-action waiver shall be valid or enforceable with respect to a case which relates to a violation
39 of this Article."
40 SECTION 2. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to acts or
41 omissions occurring on or after that date.
